"Licht S.","Efficient solar-driven synthesis, carbon capture, and desalinization, STEP: Solar thermal electrochemical production of fuels, metals, bleach",2011,"Advanced Materials","23","47",,"5592","5612",,,10.1002/adma.201103198,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-83455195192&partnerID=40&md5=186320dcf264546ec3465754c27329a3","Department of Chemistry, George Washington University, Washington, DC 20052, United States","Licht, S., Department of Chemistry, George Washington University, Washington, DC 20052, United States","STEP (solar thermal electrochemical production) theory is derived and experimentally verified for the electrosynthesis of energetic molecules at solar energy efficiency greater than any photovoltaic conversion efficiency. In STEP the efficient formation of metals, fuels, chlorine, and carbon capture is driven by solar thermal heated endothermic electrolyses of concentrated reactants occuring at a voltage below that of the room temperature energy stored in the products. One example is CO 2, which is reduced to either fuels or storable carbon at a solar efficiency of over 50% due to a synergy of efficient solar thermal absorption and electrochemical conversion at high temperature and reactant concentration. CO 2-free production of iron by STEP, from iron ore, occurs via Fe(III) in molten carbonate. Water is efficiently split to hydrogen by molten hydroxide electrolysis, and chlorine, sodium, and magnesium from molten chlorides. A pathway is provided for the STEP decrease of atmospheric carbon dioxide levels to pre-industial age levels in 10 years. Solar thermal electrochemical production (STEP) is derived and experimentally verified for the electrosynthesis of energetic molecules at solar energy efficiency greater than any photovoltaic conversion efficiency. In STEP the efficient formation of metals, fuels, chlorine, and carbon capture is driven by solar thermal heated endothermic electrolyses of concentrated reactants at high solar energy conversion efficiency. Copyright © 2011 WILEY-VCH Verlag GmbH &amp; Co. KGaA, Weinheim.","climate change; global warming; photovoltaic; sequestration; solar energy; solar fuels","Atmospheric carbon dioxide; Carbon capture; Electrochemical conversion; Energetic molecules; High temperature; Molten carbonate; Molten chlorides; Molten hydroxides; photovoltaic; Photovoltaic conversion; Reactant concentrations; Room temperature; sequestration; Solar fuels; Solar thermal; Atmospheric chemistry; Atmospheric composition; Carbon; Carbon dioxide; Chlorine; Chlorine compounds; Climate change; Conversion efficiency; Electrolysis; Fuels; Global warming; Hydrogen; Iron compounds; Iron ores; Magnesium; Photovoltaic effects; Sodium; Solar energy; Solar heating; Solar power generation; Synthesis (chemical); Energy efficiency; biofuel; carbon; carbon dioxide; ferric ion; hydrogen; hypochlorite sodium; iron; metal; sodium chloride; water; air pollution; article; chemistry; economics; electrochemistry; electrolysis; isolation and purification; photochemistry; solar energy; temperature; utilization review; Air Pollution; Biofuels; Carbon; Carbon Dioxide; Electrochemistry; Electrolysis; Ferric Compounds; Hydrogen; Iron; Metals; Photochemical Processes; Sodium Chloride; Sodium Hypochlorite; Solar Energy; Temperature; Water",,"carbon, 7440-44-0; carbon dioxide, 124-38-9, 58561-67-4; ferric ion, 20074-52-6; hydrogen, 12385-13-6, 1333-74-0; hypochlorite sodium, 7681-52-9; iron, 14093-02-8, 53858-86-9, 7439-89-6; sodium chloride, 7647-14-5; water, 7732-18-5; Biofuels; Carbon, 7440-44-0; Carbon Dioxide, 124-38-9; Ferric Compounds; Hydrogen, 1333-74-0; Iron, 7439-89-6; Metals; Sodium Chloride, 7647-14-5; Sodium Hypochlorite, 7681-52-9; Water, 7732-18-5",,,,"(2009) On Solar Hydrogen & Nanotechnology, , (Ed: L. Vayssieres), John Wiley and Sons, Weinheim, Germany; (2008) The Solar Generation of Hydrogen: Towards A Renewable Energy Future, , (Eds: K. Rajeshwar, S. Licht, R. McConnell), Springe